<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG PHILANTHROPIST GETS HONORARY DOCTORATE FROM NTNU
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  June 5 (CNA) 06/05/07  20:36:50 (By Han Nai-kuo)
</P>
<P>
National Taiwan Normal University (NTNU) awarded an honorary
doctoral degree to Hong Kong philanthropist Tin Ka-ping Tuesday
in recognition of his longstanding support for education
advancement in Hong Kong, China and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
NTNU Principal Kuo Yi-hsiung presented the honor to 88-year-old
Tin during a ceremony marking the university's  61st founding
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
Tin, a celebrated entrepreneur and long-time donor to more than
150 schools and some 800 charitable projects, announced at the
ceremony that he will donate NT$10 million (US$302,020) to NTNU.
</P>
<P>
NTNU will use the money to strengthen its programs at the College
of International Studies and Education for Overseas Chinese
located on its Linkou campus.
</P>
<P>
Tin,  who settled in Hong Kong in 1958,  is chairman of
TinsChemical Corp. and founder of the K.P. Tin Foundation. He is
known as the "father of 100 schools" because of his generous
contributions to primary schools, secondary schools and
universities. More than 40 schools in China are named after him.
</P>
<P>
He has also donated to hundreds of hospitals and charitable
organizations in China.  A recipient of many honors and awards,
Tin has been made a Member of the Order of the British Empire,
honorary citizen of over 30 provinces, cities and counties in
China and has been conferred honorary doctorates and
professorships by more than 30 universities.
</P>
